<div id="review_1514583171" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1514583171" />
    <a title="Kerri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51649609-kerri"><img alt="Kerri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1608947473p2/51649609.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1514583171?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kerri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kerri" href="/user/show/51649609-kerri">Kerri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780552131063" href="/book/show/828352.Mort">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51649609-kerri?shelf=most-loved">most-loved</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1514583171" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16925313041954620425">⏳<br/><i>“History isn&apos;t like that. History unravels gently, like an old sweater. It has been patched and darned many times, reknitted to suit different people, shoved in a box under the sink of censorship to be cut up for the dusters of propaganda, yet it always - eventually - manages to spring back into its old familiar shape. History has a habit of changing the people who think they are changing it. History always has a few tricks up its frayed sleeve. It&apos;s been around a long time.”</i><br/><br/>As brilliant as I h</span>
  <span id="freeText16925313041954620425" style="display:none">⏳<br /><i>“History isn't like that. History unravels gently, like an old sweater. It has been patched and darned many times, reknitted to suit different people, shoved in a box under the sink of censorship to be cut up for the dusters of propaganda, yet it always - eventually - manages to spring back into its old familiar shape. History has a habit of changing the people who think they are changing it. History always has a few tricks up its frayed sleeve. It's been around a long time.”</i><br /><br />As brilliant as I had hoped! That cover promised quite the story, and <i>Mort</i> seems to be a particularly loved <i>Discworld</i> book, so had high expectations, which were once again easily surpassed. I'm fascinated by Terry Pratchett's ability to have a poignant, gripping book that's also funny. Properly funny. Not the occasional funny moment that make you chuckle as you read, but the kind of funny that makes you laugh when you read it, and then pop back into your head several days later to make you laugh again. And while I'm sure they aren't for everyone, they certainly seem to work for many people. I always find that amazing, when humour can have mass appeal like that -- it's difficult to achieve, and tends to look easily simply because it's been executed by someone with real talent. <br /><br />I love Death, especially because he likes cats so much. Mort was great as well. The whole bizarre adventure was a joy to read, and I look forward to the next one!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16925313041954620425" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


