<div id="review_2984592300" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2984592300" />
    <a title="Holly (The GrimDragon)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14530641-holly-the-grimdragon"><img alt="Holly (The GrimDragon)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618118532p2/14530641.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2984592300?book_show_action=true">Sep 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Holly (The GrimDragon)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Holly (The GrimDragon)" href="/user/show/14530641-holly-the-grimdragon">Holly (The GrimDragon)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780552131063" href="/book/show/828352.Mort">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14530641-holly-the-grimdragon?shelf=fantasy-sci-fi">fantasy-sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14530641-holly-the-grimdragon?shelf=the-infinite-library">the-infinite-library</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2984592300" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10811175070043703135"><b>“There should be a word for that brief period just after waking when the mind is full of warm pink nothing. You lie there entirely empty of thought, except for a growing suspicion that heading towards you, like a sockful of damp sand in a nocturnal alleyway, are all the recollections you&apos;d really rather do without, and which amount to the fact that the only mitigating factor in your horrible future is the certainty that it will be quite short.”</b><br/><br/>Ah, yes. Why not begin a series that has approximate</span>
  <span id="freeText10811175070043703135" style="display:none"><b>“There should be a word for that brief period just after waking when the mind is full of warm pink nothing. You lie there entirely empty of thought, except for a growing suspicion that heading towards you, like a sockful of damp sand in a nocturnal alleyway, are all the recollections you'd really rather do without, and which amount to the fact that the only mitigating factor in your horrible future is the certainty that it will be quite short.”</b><br /><br />Ah, yes. Why not begin a series that has approximately 42389 books, Holly. It's not like you've started a million others or anything. This is a perfectly sane thing to do! Hahahaha! Oh no.<br /><br />Although technically the fourth book in the insanely popular Discworld series, I decided to begin with Mort because it was the one that called out to me the most. After consulting with a few Pratchett devotees, I was told that Mort is a great place to start my journey with not only Discworld, but with Sir Pratchett himself. Alrighty then, perfect!<br /><br />It's safe to say, I dug the hell out of this!<br /><br /><b>“He was determined to discover the underlying logic behind the universe.<br /><br />Which was going to be hard, because there wasn't one.”</b><br /><br />Mortimer doesn't quite fit in anywhere, including within his family who live on a farm and specialize in distilling wine from reannual grapes. Being the youngest son, his parents are unsure what to do with him. He's uninterested in working at the winery, which is for the best really because the kid is not exactly suited for such a life. He's awkward, clumsy, lanky (all knees, as they say) and easily distracted.<br /><br />Not knowing what else to do, Mort's father Lezek takes him to a nearby Employment Fair, hoping that someone will teach him a trade that he will become successful in. Unfortunately, Mort watches as one by one his fellow hopefuls are recruited, leaving him the only poor sod remaining as midnight approaches.<br /><br />That's where Death comes in, riding his white battle horse named Binky and looking for an apprentice to help assist souls into the next world. You see, Death is going through a.. well.. a midlife crisis of sorts. He's tired of his job. He's bored with his life and desperately wants to get away, take a break, have a few drinks. Maybe murder a curry or five.<br /><br />Death hires Mort to learn the ropes and possibly take over the business. Believing that his son will be serving an apprenticeship with an undertaker, Lezek is more than happy for Mortimer.<br /><br />Eventually Mort finds himself filling in for Death and that's when things go a bit bonkers. Naturally.<br /><br />I fucking adore Death as a character. SHOCKER! Speaking in all capital letters, Death is an eccentric, sarcastic, cat-lover. He tends to be a bit somber, as one would expect in the position he is in. Yet he's also incredibly weird and wonderful! I giggle-snorted more than a few times at his brilliant deadpan delivery.<br /><br />Mort was a nice change of pace. It's delightfully witty, charming and surprisingly touching. This being my very first Pratchett makes it quite special and I look forward to meeting more characters in Discworld!</span>
  <a data-text-id="10811175070043703135" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


